where it fluctuates like mad

861
00:31:40,660 --> 00:31:44,100
and then you expand about one over the temperature.

862
00:31:44,100 --> 00:31:46,180
High temperature expansions.

863
00:31:46,240 --> 00:31:47,400
They're not very hard

864
00:31:47,400 --> 00:31:48,360
and they're not very difficult,

865
00:31:49,140 --> 00:31:50,940
but it's not where we're going to go.

866
00:31:51,220 --> 00:31:52,900
Then there's another kind of method

867
00:31:52,900 --> 00:31:54,580
called renormalization group.

868
00:31:55,240 --> 00:31:57,960
That's a method that I will maybe tell you

869
00:31:57,960 --> 00:31:59,440
a little bit about as we go along,

870
00:32:00,100 --> 00:32:01,120
but not tonight.

871
00:32:01,680 --> 00:32:03,820
And the other method is called

872
00:32:03,820 --> 00:32:05,560
mean field approximation.

873
00:32:06,460 --> 00:32:08,060
And mean field approximation

874
00:32:08,060 --> 00:32:10,620
is a nice physically intuitive picture

875
00:32:11,220 --> 00:32:13,160
of how this phenomena

876
00:32:13,160 --> 00:32:16,240
of spontaneous magnetization takes place.

877
00:32:16,760 --> 00:32:18,240
That's what I want to do tonight,

878
00:32:18,400 --> 00:32:21,000
is show you the mean field description of this.

879
00:32:22,000 --> 00:32:24,460
And mean here doesn't mean nasty.

880
00:32:24,800 --> 00:32:26,400
It doesn't mean cheap.

881
00:32:26,700 --> 00:32:27,980
It means average.

882
00:32:28,580 --> 00:32:29,180
Okay.

883
00:32:29,260 --> 00:32:30,440
Mean field approximation.

884
00:32:31,600 --> 00:32:32,200
Now,

885
00:32:32,200 --> 00:32:33,140
what we're going to imagine

886
00:32:33,140 --> 00:32:35,360
is that we have a lattice.

887
00:32:43,700 --> 00:32:46,680
And it might be a three-dimensional lattice,

888
00:32:46,840 --> 00:32:49,080
which might be the case we're really interested in,

889
00:32:49,120 --> 00:32:50,560
or it might be a two-dimensional lattice.

890
00:32:51,620 --> 00:32:54,520
I don't want to deal with the one-dimensional lattice

891
00:32:54,520 --> 00:32:56,640
for reasons that perhaps we'll discuss.

892
00:32:56,960 --> 00:32:59,500
But let's start with either a two-dimensional lattice

893
00:32:59,500 --> 00:33:00,800
that I can draw on the blackboard

894
00:33:00,800 --> 00:33:02,180
or a three-dimensional lattice,

895
00:33:02,440 --> 00:33:03,760
or better yet,

896
00:33:04,860 --> 00:33:05,980
a D,

897
00:33:05,980 --> 00:33:07,640
D like David,

898
00:33:07,780 --> 00:33:09,420
a D-dimensional lattice.

899
00:33:10,340 --> 00:33:13,140
And the reason I say a D-dimensional lattice

900
00:33:13,160 --> 00:33:16,399
is because this approximation works best

901
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:18,740
when D is very large,

902
00:33:19,020 --> 00:33:20,460
for reasons that I'll explain.

903
00:33:21,020 --> 00:33:22,540
The reason is very simple.

904
00:33:22,760 --> 00:33:24,640
The reason has to do with the fact

905
00:33:24,640 --> 00:33:26,040
that the higher the dimension,

906
00:33:26,440 --> 00:33:30,920
the more neighbors that any given atom has,

907
00:33:31,240 --> 00:33:32,480
or any given site has.

908
00:33:32,900 --> 00:33:34,080
In one dimension,

909
00:33:34,360 --> 00:33:36,460
each site only has two neighbors.

910
00:33:37,660 --> 00:33:38,260
Okay?

911
00:33:38,420 --> 00:33:39,780
In a thousand dimensions,

912
00:33:40,080 --> 00:33:42,800
how many neighbors does a thousand have?

913
00:33:42,920 --> 00:33:43,140
A thousand.

914
00:33:43,160 --> 00:33:44,200
Two thousand neighbors.

915
00:33:44,860 --> 00:33:45,500
Yeah.

916
00:33:45,920 --> 00:33:48,120
Two thousand neighbors in a thousand dimensions.

917
00:33:48,540 --> 00:33:49,800
In two dimensions,

918
00:33:49,940 --> 00:33:51,260
each one has four neighbors.

919
00:33:51,720 --> 00:33:53,000
In three dimensions,

920
00:33:53,160 --> 00:33:53,560
two more,

921
00:33:53,560 --> 00:33:54,240
six neighbors.

922
00:33:54,740 --> 00:33:55,380
So,

923
00:33:55,380 --> 00:33:57,060
two D neighbors.

924
00:33:57,860 --> 00:33:58,180
Now,

925
00:33:58,180 --> 00:33:59,180
the reason it's good

926
00:33:59,180 --> 00:34:00,900
to have a lot of neighbors

927
00:34:00,900 --> 00:34:03,720
is because you can average over the neighbors.

928
00:34:04,380 --> 00:34:08,699
You can do an average over the neighbors

929
00:34:08,699 --> 00:34:11,580
and say this molecule at the center

930
00:34:11,580 --> 00:34:14,840
sees the effect of a large number of neighbors,

931
00:34:15,260 --> 00:34:16,920
and it doesn't matter much

932
00:34:16,920 --> 00:34:20,179
if one neighbor is a little bit different.

933
00:34:20,520 --> 00:34:22,739
You can average over the neighbors.

934
00:34:23,100 --> 00:34:25,139
You can use the laws of large numbers,

935
00:34:25,300 --> 00:34:25,800
so to speak,

936
00:34:25,800 --> 00:34:26,380
statistics,

937
00:34:26,560 --> 00:34:28,960
to average over the properties

938
00:34:28,960 --> 00:34:30,100
of the nearest neighbors.

939
00:34:30,520 --> 00:34:30,940
So,

940
00:34:30,940 --> 00:34:33,920
it's as if we in this room

941
00:34:34,940 --> 00:34:36,199
form the lattice,

942
00:34:36,280 --> 00:34:38,480
which you do form sitting there in your chairs,

943
00:34:38,500 --> 00:34:40,280
although it's a rather irregular lattice.

944
00:34:42,260 --> 00:34:44,540
And you're interested in the properties

945
00:34:44,540 --> 00:34:45,280
of your neighbors

946
00:34:45,280 --> 00:34:47,639
and what your neighbors are doing to you.

947
00:34:48,159 --> 00:34:48,719
Well,

948
00:34:48,719 --> 00:34:50,940
if there are enough neighbors,

949
00:34:51,159 --> 00:34:53,520
you can average over them and say

950
00:34:53,520 --> 00:34:55,780
the effect of my nearest neighbors on me

951
00:34:55,780 --> 00:34:58,160
is to have this particular effect,

952
00:34:58,360 --> 00:35:01,180
which is the average over large numbers of neighbors.

953
00:35:01,440 --> 00:35:03,320
If there's only one or two neighbors,

954
00:35:03,640 --> 00:35:06,100
then averaging over them

955
00:35:06,100 --> 00:35:08,280
might be a less effective thing to do.

956
00:35:08,380 --> 00:35:10,160
And this is true for this kind of system.

957
00:35:10,160 --> 00:35:10,940
So,

958
00:35:10,940 --> 00:35:13,460
the mean field approximation

959
00:35:14,500 --> 00:35:15,700
becomes accurate,

960
00:35:15,700 --> 00:35:17,840
infinitely accurate

961
00:35:17,840 --> 00:35:18,840
or perfectly accurate,

962
00:35:19,020 --> 00:35:20,680
in the limit of large numbers of dimensions.

963
00:35:20,980 --> 00:35:22,060
But we're not really interested

964
00:35:22,060 --> 00:35:23,520
in the limit of large number of dimensions.

965
00:35:24,020 --> 00:35:24,620
Well,

966
00:35:24,620 --> 00:35:26,200
it turns out numerically

967
00:35:26,200 --> 00:35:31,040
that two is a little bit large

968
00:35:31,040 --> 00:35:32,740
and three is large already.

969
00:35:33,040 --> 00:35:33,620
In other words,

970
00:35:33,620 --> 00:35:34,660
mean field approximation

971
00:35:34,660 --> 00:35:37,180
works pretty well for three dimensions.

972
00:35:38,100 --> 00:35:40,140
But more important than that,

973
00:35:40,160 --> 00:35:41,720
than whether it works numerically well,

974
00:35:41,880 --> 00:35:44,020
is it gives you a picture of what happens

975
00:35:44,020 --> 00:35:46,460
that leads to this magnetization.

976
00:35:47,160 --> 00:35:47,860
All right,

977
00:35:47,860 --> 00:35:48,020
now,

978
00:35:48,020 --> 00:35:49,440
we're going to invent now

979
00:35:49,440 --> 00:35:50,880
an energy function.

980
00:35:51,640 --> 00:35:53,060
An energy function

981
00:35:58,320 --> 00:36:00,600
which is the energy function,

982
00:36:01,280 --> 00:36:01,800
well,

983
00:36:01,800 --> 00:36:04,060
for this system of atoms.

984
00:36:04,200 --> 00:36:05,600
Each one is either up or down.

985
00:36:05,760 --> 00:36:07,980
Let's represent an up by a dot

986
00:36:07,980 --> 00:36:09,660
and a down by a cross.

987
00:36:11,020 --> 00:36:16,900
The energy only depends on the orientation configuration

988
00:36:16,900 --> 00:36:18,400
of nearest neighbors.

989
00:36:18,920 --> 00:36:19,880
All right?

990
00:36:19,920 --> 00:36:22,600
The energy is low when they're parallel

991
00:36:22,940 --> 00:36:25,520
and high when they're anti-parallel.

992
00:36:26,360 --> 00:36:27,120
So,

993
00:36:27,120 --> 00:36:29,320
here's an expression which does that.

994
00:36:30,720 --> 00:36:32,200
Let's take the energy

995
00:36:33,879 --> 00:36:35,200
to just be,

996
00:36:35,200 --> 00:36:38,720
let's call it sigma of i,

997
00:36:39,360 --> 00:36:40,420
sigma of j,

998
00:36:40,680 --> 00:36:42,360
but now i and j represent

999
00:36:43,120 --> 00:36:44,880
neighboring points on the lattice.

1000
00:36:45,600 --> 00:36:47,560
As you range over i and j,

1001
00:36:47,700 --> 00:36:49,120
I really only want you to imagine

1002
00:36:49,120 --> 00:36:51,900
that you're ranging over nearest neighbors.

1003
00:36:52,800 --> 00:36:55,600
Nearest neighbors are on the lattice.

1004
00:36:56,340 --> 00:36:58,480
And let's put a minus sign in here.

1005
00:36:59,820 --> 00:37:00,340
Now,

1006
00:37:00,340 --> 00:37:02,800
if sigma i and sigma j are the same,

1007
00:37:03,800 --> 00:37:04,680
in other words,

1008
00:37:04,680 --> 00:37:06,640
if they're both plus one or minus one,

1009
00:37:07,440 --> 00:37:08,560
then sigma i,

1010
00:37:08,560 --> 00:37:09,520
sigma j is one,

1011
00:37:09,780 --> 00:37:11,220
and the energy is negative.

1012
00:37:11,680 --> 00:37:12,740
Negative is low.

1013
00:37:13,560 --> 00:37:14,240
All right,

1014
00:37:14,240 --> 00:37:16,280
so this favors or lowers the energy

1015
00:37:16,280 --> 00:37:17,120
when they're parallel.

1016
00:37:17,240 --> 00:37:18,780
What about when they're anti-parallel?

1017
00:37:18,960 --> 00:37:20,880
When they're anti-parallel,

1018
00:37:20,880 --> 00:37:23,600
then the energy is plus one.

1019
00:37:24,160 --> 00:37:26,480
And so there's two units of energy

1020
00:37:27,960 --> 00:37:31,220
stored in every bond

1021
00:37:31,840 --> 00:37:33,920
if the bond is a broken bond.

1022
00:37:34,240 --> 00:37:34,440
Now,

1023
00:37:34,440 --> 00:37:35,740
what do I mean by a broken bond?

1024
00:37:35,740 --> 00:37:37,940
Let's say an unbroken bond

1025
00:37:38,740 --> 00:37:41,860
is a bond where the spins are parallel.

1026
00:37:42,360 --> 00:37:44,080
Here's an unbroken bond.

1027
00:37:44,220 --> 00:37:47,580
A bond means a nearest neighbor link of the lattice.

1028
00:37:48,320 --> 00:37:51,420
Here's another bond which is unbroken.

1029
00:37:51,740 --> 00:37:54,140
The spins are parallel at the two ends of it.

1030
00:37:54,420 --> 00:37:57,300
A broken bond would be one

1031
00:37:57,300 --> 00:37:59,680
like this one over here,

1032
00:37:59,820 --> 00:38:01,820
where the spins are anti-parallel.

1033
00:38:02,320 --> 00:38:04,380
Broken bonds cost you energy.

1034
00:38:04,380 --> 00:38:06,200
How much energy?

1035
00:38:06,360 --> 00:38:09,720
Each broken bond costs you two units of energy.

1036
00:38:10,180 --> 00:38:11,920
So energetically,

1037
00:38:11,920 --> 00:38:13,260
it's profitable

1038
00:38:13,260 --> 00:38:16,420
to keep the number of broken bonds to a minimum.

1039
00:38:16,800 --> 00:38:18,280
But on the other hand,

1040
00:38:18,280 --> 00:38:20,160
as you raise the temperature,

1041
00:38:20,920 --> 00:38:23,700
because there are so many possible configurations

1042
00:38:23,700 --> 00:38:25,020
with broken bonds,

1043
00:38:25,740 --> 00:38:28,000
raising the temperature will tend to create

1044
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:30,020
a population of broken bonds there.

1045
00:38:30,240 --> 00:38:30,640
All right,

1046
00:38:30,640 --> 00:38:31,540
so that's the picture.

1047
00:38:32,060 --> 00:38:32,660
Now,

1048
00:38:32,660 --> 00:38:33,640
we're going to do

1049
00:38:33,640 --> 00:38:35,600
an interesting approximation,

1050
00:38:35,940 --> 00:38:38,420
which really captures some of the interesting physics.

1051
00:38:39,220 --> 00:38:41,320
Let's focus on one molecule.

1052
00:38:42,900 --> 00:38:45,060
Let's focus on this molecule right over here.

1053
00:38:45,120 --> 00:38:48,420
I don't know whether it's up or down,

1054
00:38:48,560 --> 00:38:49,680
so I haven't biased it,

1055
00:38:49,800 --> 00:38:51,920
but let's focus on this one over here.

1056
00:38:53,620 --> 00:38:57,360
And let's write the expression for its energy.

1057
00:38:58,620 --> 00:38:59,620
Its energy,

1058
00:38:59,620 --> 00:39:03,620
let's call this sigma z.

1059
00:39:03,640 --> 00:39:06,120
That's sigma zero right at the center.

1060
00:39:06,360 --> 00:39:09,400
The spin that I'm focusing on is called sigma zero.

1061
00:39:09,540 --> 00:39:10,940
It's plus one or minus one.

1062
00:39:11,700 --> 00:39:14,620
And it interacts with all of its nearest neighbors.

1063
00:39:14,960 --> 00:39:16,340
So its energy,

1064
00:39:16,340 --> 00:39:18,320
the energy of sigma zero,

1065
00:39:18,380 --> 00:39:20,360
let's call it little e.

1066
00:39:20,760 --> 00:39:24,220
Little e represents the energy of this spin

1067
00:39:24,960 --> 00:39:28,080
in the background of all of its neighbors.

1068
00:39:28,480 --> 00:39:29,660
And what is it?

1069
00:39:29,720 --> 00:39:32,280
It's minus sigma zero times.

1070
00:39:33,640 --> 00:39:35,430
The sum of all the

1071
00:39:35,430 --> 00:39:37,220
spins of all the nearest neighbors.

1072
00:39:38,160 --> 00:39:42,480
Sum of the nearest neighbors of the nearest neighbor spins.

1073
00:39:42,740 --> 00:39:44,160
I'm not going to try to make too much,

1074
00:39:44,180 --> 00:39:45,120
that's enough terminology,

1075
00:39:45,120 --> 00:39:46,940
enough indexology.

1076
00:39:48,160 --> 00:39:48,760
Okay?

1077
00:39:49,940 --> 00:39:57,180
Let's suppose that the spins have an average value.

1078
00:39:58,540 --> 00:39:59,140
Okay?

1079
00:39:59,200 --> 00:40:02,340
An average value that the system has magnetized.

1080
00:40:03,040 --> 00:40:03,760
Let's suppose,

1081
00:40:03,760 --> 00:40:04,560
it may not be,

1082
00:40:04,560 --> 00:40:05,960
we'll find out if it's not.

1083
00:40:06,160 --> 00:40:07,140
In other words,

1084
00:40:07,140 --> 00:40:09,380
let's suppose that on the average,

1085
00:40:10,380 --> 00:40:13,920
each spin has the same value as each other spin.

1086
00:40:14,400 --> 00:40:16,580
And let's suppose on the average,

1087
00:40:16,860 --> 00:40:21,260
the average of any spin is called s.

1088
00:40:22,060 --> 00:40:22,580
Now,

1089
00:40:22,580 --> 00:40:25,240
s is a number between minus one and one.

1090
00:40:25,500 --> 00:40:27,050
The average of a thing which

1091
00:40:27,050 --> 00:40:28,600
can only be one or minus one

1092
00:40:28,600 --> 00:40:30,920
must lie between one and minus one.

1093
00:40:30,920 --> 00:40:31,840
So,

1094
00:40:31,840 --> 00:40:32,980
whatever s is,

1095
00:40:34,280 --> 00:40:35,520
the average spin,

1096
00:40:35,720 --> 00:40:37,420
is between one and minus one.

1097
00:40:37,640 --> 00:40:40,280
s is the thing which is called the mean field.

1098
00:40:40,660 --> 00:40:42,060
The average field,

1099
00:40:42,060 --> 00:40:44,080
the average value of all of the spins.

1100
00:40:46,880 --> 00:40:47,700
And now,

1101
00:40:47,700 --> 00:40:50,740
each one of these spins sees around it

1102
00:40:50,740 --> 00:40:52,520
a whole bunch of spins.

1103
00:40:52,820 --> 00:40:55,520
If the dimensionality of the system is high enough,

1104
00:40:55,780 --> 00:40:58,640
it sees loads and loads of spins around it.

1105
00:40:58,640 --> 00:41:02,600
And so it has some average energy in the background.

1106
00:41:02,760 --> 00:41:04,100
This one has an energy in

1107
00:41:04,100 --> 00:41:05,440
the background of all of these.

1108
00:41:06,460 --> 00:41:08,460
And what is its energy?

1109
00:41:09,040 --> 00:41:11,940
It's just equal to minus sigma naught

1110
00:41:13,480 --> 00:41:14,000
times,

1111
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:15,220
now on the average,

1112
00:41:15,280 --> 00:41:17,220
each one of these sigmas is equal to s.

1113
00:41:17,800 --> 00:41:18,320
So,

1114
00:41:18,320 --> 00:41:19,140
that's n,

1115
00:41:19,140 --> 00:41:20,800
or sorry,

1116
00:41:20,800 --> 00:41:21,860
that's twice d

1117
00:41:23,680 --> 00:41:24,520
times s.

1118
00:41:24,820 --> 00:41:25,980
Why twice d?

1119
00:41:29,759 --> 00:41:31,720
That's because that's the number of nearest neighbors.

1120
00:41:31,980 --> 00:41:33,600
Twice d is the number of nearest neighbors.

1121
00:41:34,240 --> 00:41:36,860
So I've replaced each one of these by its average.

1122
00:41:37,440 --> 00:41:38,840
There are two d of them.

1123
00:41:39,160 --> 00:41:41,040
And so that particular spin,

1124
00:41:41,040 --> 00:41:41,980
right at the center,

1125
00:41:43,220 --> 00:41:46,040
is experiencing a bias

1126
00:41:47,480 --> 00:41:49,220
or a effective energy

1127
00:41:49,220 --> 00:41:51,920
which is proportional to that spin

1128
00:41:53,520 --> 00:41:55,180
with a minus sign,

1129
00:41:55,180 --> 00:41:55,820
whatever it is.

1130
00:41:55,940 --> 00:41:56,260
Now,

1131
00:41:56,260 --> 00:41:57,900
s can either be positive or negative.

1132
00:41:57,900 --> 00:42:01,020
We don't know offhand whether s is positive or negative.

1133
00:42:02,320 --> 00:42:03,400
They may all be,

1134
00:42:03,400 --> 00:42:04,540
they may have a tendency,

1135
00:42:04,900 --> 00:42:05,860
maybe zero,

1136
00:42:05,860 --> 00:42:08,120
maybe on the average s is equal to zero.

1137
00:42:09,960 --> 00:42:10,440
Then,

1138
00:42:10,440 --> 00:42:12,220
this would not be magnetized.

1139
00:42:13,279 --> 00:42:16,100
It's magnetized if s is not zero.

1140
00:42:17,200 --> 00:42:18,720
And s can either be positive,

1141
00:42:18,720 --> 00:42:19,720
or it can be negative,

